Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."],"variants":[{"name":"Aimie","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]},{"name":"Aimée","meanings":["originally a vernacular nickname meaning ‘beloved’, from the past participle of French <i>aimer</i> ‘to love’ (Latin <i>amare</i>;  compare  Amy  ). It has been in use in French since the Middle Ages, although it has never been very common. It is now also used, with or without the accent, as a given name in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Amie","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Amy  , corresponding in form to the French vocabulary word meaning ‘(female) friend’."]},{"name":"Ami","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Amy Langston was born in 1350, in Bodmin, Cornwall, England, her father, SIR THOMAS LANGSTON, was 21 and her mother, LADY ANN ROCHFORD, was 20. She married Sir Thomas Moyle in 1369, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1400, in Cornwall, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1350–1400":"1350–1400","1345–1434":"1345–1434","1328–Male":"1328–Surnud","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1329–Male":"1329–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1434":"1434","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Bodmin, Cornwall, England":"Bodmin, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1350–1400":"1350–1400","1345–1434":"1345–1434","1328–Male":"1328–Kuollut","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1329–Male":"1329–Kuollut","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1434":"1434","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Bodmin, Cornwall, England":"Bodmin, Cornwall, England"},"fr":{"1350–1400":"1350–1400","1345–1434":"1345–1434","1328–Male":"1328–Décédé","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1329–Male":"1329–Décédé","1330–Female":"1330–Décédée","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1434":"1434","1400":"1400","1345":"1345","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre","Cornwall, England":"Cornouailles, Angleterre","Bodmin, Cornwall, England":"Bodmin, Cornouailles, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Amy Langston est née en 1350, à Bodmin, Cornouailles, Angleterre, son père, SIR THOMAS LANGSTON, avait 21 ans et sa mèr